A Republican Strategy to Oppose Obama’s Re-election
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policies with the need to fight the election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by confirming that election fraud in the United States is rarer than the number of people killed by lightning strikes.
Republican lawyers have reported only 300 cases of election fraud in the U.S. in 10 years.
One thing is for sure: these new rules will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for carrying out the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, the majority of U.S. governments have announced new laws since 2009 that complicate the procedure for registration or the receipt of a certificate.
This phenomenon gained importance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were recorded in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone that restrict the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, declare the right to register as an elector on election day invalid, and grant citizens the right to vote for which a court act is available.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state has asked voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana's law.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that will force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that U.S. citizens, unlike Quebec, do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible persons, do not have a photo ID issued by a government authority in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an ID.
However, more than a hundred dollars are often to be paid in order to obtain the required ID.
Young people, minorities and low-income people are disproportionately affected by the new restrictions.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with incomes less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This is even more than enough.
Students who are considered to be voters who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations to vote more strongly for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Prior to 2004, no state had asked for proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws that require voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Spanish votes.
Because it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican lawmakers in eight states promoted laws that abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, campaigns to register voters in the 2004 general election have contributed to the registration of approximately 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the number of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early voter turnout.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-American, although they make up only 13% of the state's electorate.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of the electorate, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites, who represented 76% of the electorate, made up only 46% of the electorate who voted in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several bills were blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to exonerate the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote.
Democratic critics deplore the party-political nature of the passed laws and see in them the clear goal of influencing the results in the states that are hitting for 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required in the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the legislation on the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is for sure: these new rules will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Early detection of prostate cancer: should the test be done or not?
