The Higgs Boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson has sparked some attention last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted from the standard model – our best or “at least wrong” explanation of nature and the behavior of matter – but empirically has not yet been observed.
But for physicists, it is not yet entirely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs-Boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this appears to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely sure about it.
Let’s assume, however, that it’s actually the Higgs, since there seems to be only a small risk of cheating, and let’s look at what it is about.
There is an inevitably unavoidable law in this world that causes two objects not to be present at the same place at the same time.
It’s not possible to break this rule – and don’t try too hard because you’ll hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that they also have such a law: the Pauli exclusion principle, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantity state" and are in the same "quantum state" while in the same "gap."
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens, who are referred to as fermions and obey politely the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons are moving, an evil gang of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred – certainly not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratories’ The Particle Adventure website, these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not deal with here and the “force particles” through which the great forces of nature are spreading and with which the Higgs boson is somehow connected.
It must be emphasized here, however, that these bosons are not all exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "particle of light", which is the "bot" of electromagnetic force.
That is, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly at this location, in the form of a silt that was thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carrier of force".
Stabilized field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" in order for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the trigger must reach very high energies, a little like a frozen pond whose surface could only be feared by a very large rock.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like CERN – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! – is needed to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don’t – for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself on the refrigerator.
And equally not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (by the way, the photon) do not have a mass.
What can all this research be “good for now,” Ms. Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to examine all deviations between the observations and predictions of SM in detail.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who most hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and close some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has major flaws, since it offers no explanation for the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN so far.
Effects
The impact of these studies on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there were none.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first permanent laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was initially seen rather than a "laboratory toy".
Just imagine...
In addition, applications can also be derived from all the instruments that surround the research.
Willard Boyle, for example, developed a small light sensor during his work in optics in 1969.
Although it wasn’t the original purpose, this sensor now serves as the “eye” of all digital cameras worldwide and has been awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you really can never know it...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
