“Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man is pinching in his standing,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois’ home.
Returning to the childhood phase is an unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
“It depends on the person’s ability to take a step back,” he notes.
Because according to several people who work in palliative care, large events take place amidst these setbacks.
The patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overcrowded by the doctors and nurses who take care of them with so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But because of the illness, I really got to know my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
