Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more enjoyable.
In Quebec, there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 inhabitants.
This is very little considering that one day we will all die.
Here life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The deceased is given oral care with Brandy or Pepsi as desired.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is a part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help relatives and patients alike,” says Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, there is no day like the other.
In addition to a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family reunion in the yard and is well supported by his pillows, while touching to his honor, a young man of 36 years, who has everything from his parents, his wife, to his two young children, he is surrounded by verses.
“For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois come from their homes, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care to alleviate the suffering of patients who have reached the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor Gadbois Home and the Montreal-wide Society for Home Palliative Care specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
Exactly this great inadequacy in Quebec’s health care ensures that several doctors specializing in palliative care face the adoption of a law regulating death and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent palliative care personalities such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone has the right to quality palliative care before being accepted to go to death care.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain, without taking any measures to relieve her.
I’m afraid that patients just want to die because they don’t get adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients, despite the worst prognosis, until the last day.
The chances of survival of Hél<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard were already minimal when she discontinued a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop treatment, she replied that she regretted giving up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was in the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the caregiver for not meeting this wish after their pain has been relieved by a palliative care team.
However, it must be made clear that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which leads to the patient either sporadically or permanently falling asleep until the time of his death.
We can no longer act as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to put me to sleep,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
