With 15,000 computers on the network, some 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After Bitcoin’s price peaked at $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, it fell to $2, five months later, before recovering to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "competitive with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the “Credits” that are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy by playing (and sometimes even redeem).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, the trade is controlled and processed each time by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously account holders, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data associated with this transaction is signed electronically by a dual encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the Bitcoins traded are present in the public accounts’ account spread across the network.
The crucial step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This is done via a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clearer electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay twice for cheating very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward will be halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to a hundred millionths, which leaves a certain amount of room for play.
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement in the computational performance.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also highlights this deficiency.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the blogging platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the bill and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "mega-closed sale" was launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions that are therefore cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who insures that it has thousands of users.
It is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are covered in favour of more horizontally aligned systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to get through, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
By the way, in its report, the ECB intends to re-evaluate the various risks that are considered high today in the event of the success of this currency.
