A Constitution with the Breaking Rod in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt has decided to put everything on a map in relation to the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily gives it unlimited power, more than ever, it remains divided.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this plenary two additional months to complete his work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been relying on an interim text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only contributed to an even stronger division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "walk with the law".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that there is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, forcing the brothers to refrain from their plans to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy while the protests are raging across the country.
According to confirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will be willing to vote.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to an hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited power of attorney", the latter should probably end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a bizarre atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals did not comply with the request.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they felt that they were not able to put their views into practice.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted in the same way.
In order to achieve the decision-making ability, 11 persons, deputy members, were added in all haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly unanimously adopted.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... in the time of prayer came to be expressed, as some members of the board felt that the pendulum clock of the Constituent Assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew all attention to itself, ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The liberals, who see this only as a propaganda attack, are responding to "sacrificial sanctity".
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place over other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which recognizes Al-Azhar University as an advisory function, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with Sharia laws.
According to the Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people who are asked for an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
You can see here the first signs of a theocracy.”
The fears of the liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is far less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, no concrete religious commitment can be recognized.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, that "there may be ambiguity in relation to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One here refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, note. d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil courts are competent to decide on it."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticized for the far-reaching powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In line with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to the National Defence Council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights associations have called for.
The latter also share their fears regarding the text, which they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The record of blasphemy is maintained, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to free expression, especially for the press.
In addition, the article no longer refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In your opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect sacred places, the navel of the world and a sea of sol
The Promised Land combines in itself the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and unspoilt nature.
AIF gives you the five most important reasons to visit Israel.
Bend in front of the holy places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding celebration, the walking on the water, the silence of the storm of the sea and the fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to His disciples after the Resurrection.
Most of the shrines are located in Jerusalem.
Here believers take the path of suffering or the way of the cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretoria, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the Tomb Church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
In Christian view, the navel of the world is here, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the holiest place of the Jews - the Complaint Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 A.D.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes there, which then go into fulfillment.
Take a journey to the heights
The ruins of the fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hideout from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in the year 25 AD.
They are located on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters is the famous ski resort Hermon, where it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the mountaintop.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With just one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There are preserved ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea scrolls found in rock caves in the Jewish desert, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There the collection of works of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is on display.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and bathers.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Rally Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most comprehensive department is the Children’s Monument, which was built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When you enter the room, there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Do something for your health
The three most important recreational areas of Israel are on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 <0xC2><0xB0>C and the air warms up to 23 <0xC2><0xB0>C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there is bathing all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and thus even carries non-swimming smoothly on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt soles) and healing mud as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to soothe the nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Age
These secrets lie in the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city, the famous sea route connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and here Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with which he lived a long and happy life in that place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets, named after the zodiac sign.
Fortune is supposed to be the legend after all who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newly married couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo appointments.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater and conquer the fortress of the crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of the Roman statesmen, including Pontius Pilate.
Evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre today.
List of attractions for tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
You’d rather take the money on the trip not in euros, but in dollars, which can be exchanged easily in shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed tram and in Haifa the only subway line in the country with six stations that connect the sub-city to the super-city.
Precisely speaking, it is an underground cable car.
A ride within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which includes transfers for a ride of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only cozy food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without shellfish and foods that contain both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with ham and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falcon) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-groomed cats that are cozy and unobtrusively scattered through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
Cats like lively places and don’t say no to treats.
A rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the brand.
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bicycle rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreational seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the United States and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists arrived in the Promised Land, which is an increase of 51% compared to the 2010 comparison period, before the lifting of the visa requirement on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Mighty" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While lawmakers and lawmakers discuss the benefits of the Law on Compulsory Language Tests for Migrants, criminals are already dealing with fake certificates.
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families left in the home.
On December 1, a law came into force, according to which every working migrant must pass a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this regulation only applies to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing industry and in retail.
However, the tests are expected to become mandatory for all guest workers in the future, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
It is not only necessary to take language tests, but also tests into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for the purpose of obtaining and prolonging the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who received their education certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, Problems and Protection of Rights
The totality of examinations will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of People's Friendship, the Moscow State University, the Saint Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Agency.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the press several times before the law came into force: What does the whole thing actually bring?
What changes does the requirement to have to present language skills, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Most importantly, according to the spokespersons of the immigration authority, it is about reducing the number of forced workers.
“Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of migrant workers,” says the head of the representation of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan, Viktor Sebelev.
However, your rights must already be protected from your departure.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a profession, education, language skills and medical examinations face problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably meet people with evil intentions who put him under the pretext of helping in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of his equal months without food and documents and 12 to 14 hours on the day.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrants.
"In the homeland you will be promised one, and on arrival you will be deceived, get their passports taken away, and not receive the promised salary," Tolib Shwaripow, the head of the Tajik Immigration Administration, said in a statement.
Don't moan, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they not only do not master the language of the country of destination, but also can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford only a reasonable basic education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
“It’s hard without language skills,” they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists underscore the following important aspect regarding the law.
Only migrants with legal status are required to take the test.
If you do not have this status, then there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers remain illegal in Russia.
"Welcome" or "No access for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, the legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be done quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The employees of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and then there are cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Don't shy away from costs for false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants can be faked.
Some false certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Agency.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get it for nothing: every migrant who hoped to be able to save himself the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
That is more than twice the cost of the official test: this costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be purchased easily, both civil servants and civil servants agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who pass the test for the first time that they will be given time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered positions in areas where no active comprehension with people is necessary.
Interior Ministry Ignores Illegal Weapons Market
Extremely low share of legal weapons in criminal offences
The Russian Interior Ministry plans to tighten the Arms Act for private gun owners.
The authorities are responding to the latest events: wounded in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the amok by Moscow lawyer Dmitri Winogradow.
The police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and set the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Jarowaja, and promised that the amendments to the Weapons Act will be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not all are satisfied with the fact that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "drawing the screws".
An open letter has been published on the Internet, the author of which - representatives of various arms associations - calls on the authorities to refrain from "useless exacerbations".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal justice, Vasily Lesnikow, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from operating on the black market.
Currently, according to the authors, you can find any weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons come to the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts weapons orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez said.
On the second channel come illegal weapons, which are stolen from law enforcement agencies by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons that were stolen from both the police’s arms chambers and directly from employees of the law enforcement agencies.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons depots.
In many military camps, there were frequent explosions.
“There is evidence that in some cases it was a fire foundation to cover up the lack of weapons,” the former military official said.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
“Today, there are countless private armament factories that are not able to withstand international competition and therefore are wasting arms on the black market, for example in Moscow,” the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is the smuggling.
In particular, many guns and guns come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
“There is a production of its own, sometimes handicrafts, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling,” the former military official explains.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts calculated how much each of the five channels accounted for in supplying the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on portals on the topic of weapons.
The majority of the illegal weapons, according to investigators, come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of all weapons on the black market are there because of the "debt of those responsible who have come to terms with weapons in their work," the report says.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict zones, 14% come from thefts in weapon production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a gun shop who doesn’t want to be named assures that weapons found at illegal excavations have long since been outdated.
According to him, it is more common for dealers to provide supplies in a weapons warehouse.
A gun, such as a TT gun, is purchased via a fencing line.
The weapon is displayed and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, know about everything and therefore, if they cannot comply with the plan to detect crimes, periodically conduct check purchases at dealers who offer illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
