It attracts the ability to manipulate virtual objects in the air with just hands and create virtual open spaces.
- Please describe briefly what research your group is conducting.
- We deal with the interaction of human and machine, but want to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, most of humanity has been stuck in the phase in which it is working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes also touched.
However, we want to anticipate 5-10 years and anticipate the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, Xbox consoles and Kinect sensors are an advance, and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What else do we have in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, a lot still takes place on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We are trying to change that, working on real three-dimensional representation systems based on different technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more understandable.
For this, however, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his surroundings are recognized.
Then we could complement the real world much more easily with virtual objects.
And first of all, we should get rid of these vicious virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
She's popular, but isn't she overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform everyone about his actions and intentions.
In fact, any type of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the field of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project where we experimented with short and scarce, rather than exhaustive gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a watch.
But overall, however, the future belongs to mixed types of control, for example, gesture and language.
- What do you mean?
- For example, would you ask me to give you this squirrel box?
They say it and at the same time point to it.
- Normally I'm just saying it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to tell.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can afford at the time and what doesn’t?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approximation.
I think that in the coming time, we will have to work primarily on the development of new types of sensors that will allow us to more accurately capture people's reactions.
These can be laser sensors, for example, as they provide a good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- What claims do you make based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors on modern cameras?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or something else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
So all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work to do.
It is necessary to take into account not only the resolution along the X- and the Y-, but also along the Z-axis.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
The human movements are extremely dynamic and, frankly, the current 30 fps are not enough for gestures in particular.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor in our lab in Redmond with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction of man and machine.
For my work I needed exactly this device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the depth of the object.
More cameras might be able to solve the problem...
Or intensify the problem, as more calculations would be needed.
It would be nice to have a flexible, kinect-like system where we could play with different camera tendencies to see how that helps us in three-dimensional positioning.
