The question of breeding in the wild was first addressed by the researchers with regard to the flora.
Already half a century ago, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of the peas in orbit did not differ in the slightest from the terrestrial species.
It followed the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, guardian eggs were sent into space to investigate the effects of gravity on the development of embryos.
It develops a normal chick.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick has to find a hold; it has to be able to stand on its legs and start moving," explains Vladimir Sychew, the laboratory head of the RAN Institute for Medical and Biological Problems.
Without solid ground, the chicks overlapped wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns were completely muted.
The chicks did not respond to light and noise.
Four days later, she simply died.
“Twice we let the chicks slip and put the whole thing in place because it’s simply impossible to work with them there,” says Vladimir Sychev, referring to the failed experiment with the chicks in the room.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
In the spring of 2013, the experiments will continue.
However, only same-sex species will be found on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that had already been fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
