Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency (ESA) at a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the Member States of the European Space Agency (ESA), Poland being the second member of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s journey into space probably started much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish space enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, and they did not always come to terms with it.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld of December 6, 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
<0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the REP Hirsch Prize in 1934 for "Entrance to Cosmonautics" by Robert Esnault-Peltterie and André Louis Hirsch.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important defender of astronomy and space.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's internationally recognized contribution to the development of space was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the Earth-facing side of the moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway-draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket engine was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the design and the details of this project remain unknown.
It is not yet clear whether the rocket should be used to start or brake the draisine.
The information for this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-propelled artillery.
The research was conducted by the Institute Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents transmitted, it is clear that the research had progressed to the stage of practical tests.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Armed Forces.
In 1937, the draft of a photoelectric hunting rocket from Ing. Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski appeared in the press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda povietrzna i rakietobomba lonnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the missile propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work, its work was terminated from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space travel are devoted.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space company.
At the time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be expected that space exploration would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish space company PTA made an effort to join the International Federation for Space, which was founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a regular member as early as the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA Chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been involved in the development of the extremely successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1,800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>d<0xC3><0xB3>w Desert began flight tests with the two-stage missile RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
A further stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for observation of altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was halted.
The successor to the first RM missiles was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
From these missiles were developed three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A missile had a transport space with a capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B with a capacity of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C with a capacity of 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight altitude for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
After that, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland’s accession to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimir Remek.
The repeal of the Law on Non-Profit Work is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court lifted the Law on Non-Profit Works.
This decision sparked a lively discussion in the public.
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
The liberally oriented economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in a permanent conflict with each other.
The reason for this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of labour (wages) there are price tensions.
This is to be understood as a condition in which the manufacturer attempts to maintain economic competition by importing favourable goods by "subjecting" competition in order to gain a larger market share and increase its profits.
To a large extent, this means for most companies to move their production abroad or buy it cheaply, or to give up their business, resulting in high unemployment in countries with comparatively high labour costs.
Since private capital does not bear any social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment caused by it, the state expenditure necessarily increases.
This situation is further reinforced by the absolute unwillingness of the entrepreneurs to pay their taxes and thereby to compensate for the overall economic and social damage caused by them.
This situation is generally known, so that concrete statistics at this point are superfluous.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates a situation in the individual economies in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments deliver their own populations without regard for the social consequences of private capital.
This is expressed in particular in amendments to applicable laws.
The aim of these measures is to force the own population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially in the wage field.
This is done, on the one hand, by economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment, and, on the other, by the reduction of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as growing differences between poverty and wealth.
In Germany, there have been public food outlets for poor people who are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work for several years.
The number of people affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regularly cases where workers receive such a low wage that the state must raise their income to the minimum of existence.
Such a scandal was also uncovered in the case of aid workers employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all EU southern countries will undoubtedly be in the same condition where people are forced to emigrate under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of their social level (as was the case in the 19th century when this was the case), or for a starvation wage at the edge of society.
Naturally, the question arises here, where does this capital come from?
If it comes from another EU country, only poverty moves from one country to another; or capital stays the same, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or in Africa, workers work for a fraction of European wages.
This concerns all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and media claim to the point that the state must not participate with capital in its own economy, and that planning economics leads to economic disaster.
Private capital holds tightly on its position that the state must not intervene in an orderly manner in the economy.
Then one must wonder whether private capital does not influence politics and thus the entire state in its own selfish sense or even directs it.
Here is the clear answer: yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a virtually omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, mutual advantage, legislation in which virtually everything is criminal, but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that, in the absence of finance, a State Ministry is tasked with drafting bills by private law firms closely interconnected with industry.
These bills will then be passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer proceeds from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups who prefer their own interests.
Obviously, liberal democracies are now rapidly getting into a situation, as Appian describes in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic in the days of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had long been understood to be in disintegration, and the offices were occupied with violence.
For lubricant money, through illegal lubrication of advantages or with stone and sword.
Corruption grew indelibly, and the people went to the polls with already bought votes" ... "People of character did not apply for offices, so that the state as a result of this decline he did not have a consul for eight months" ... "Man really began to talk about the one who was in the medical profession.
As can be seen, today’s society, as in antiquity, is based on the ruthless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to general societal interests.
Private capital, by its very nature, is not able to recognize and enforce the benefit to society as a whole.
The result, today as at the time, is an unprecedented decadence of elites who are not at all striving for deeper reforms.
We must therefore look for the cause of the rise of fascism and communism in the ruthless liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From the present state of affairs, the demise of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause in which the next round is already taking place.
Particularly disastrous is the fact that today’s elites face the potential loss of hundreds of thousands of lives in the future, the humanitarian and social disasters we are already witnessing today, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from older and newer history, in complete ignorance.
The repeal of the Law on Non-Profit Works is not a solution here, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to lower the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The only solution is targeted political and social reforms that increase the state’s share of capital in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government, and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
