The movie Argo: When It's Worst, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrative Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the fallen Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had maintained patronage over his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government – it could not afford to throw the shah overboard, as this would have severely damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution was aimed at the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to free the hostages made everything worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages at home provoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the defeat of Jimmy Carters against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Just before the embassy was occupied, six embassies managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to cover up their true identity – they traveled tarnished with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who allegedly ran the country for a sci-fi film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by "Exfiltration" expert, Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to be credible, articles about this film project appeared in journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful house piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels in the film vary - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the filming of the same situations there are no major differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which ironically and slightly overspread therefore come.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the office floor, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable reboot of his career with this film.
A smiling actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor, he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after Krimi No Child's Play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller City without Grace (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film that does not play in the director's hometown Boston.
The feel for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that deflected this director’s previous films from the Hollywood Standard.
Affleck, however, also demonstrates this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the entry sequence of the first storm of the message is very impressive in its clarity, and yet conveys the feeling of confusion and the unpredictability when history occurs.
Affleck and his team also have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the false film bar at a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story doesn’t actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
However, with the few, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality a little - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at Tehran airport is turned away by a phone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide spread, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have earned more space, and thus they are far from being alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses some traction, which is a film that you can follow with a certain interest and enjoy the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 1970s.
However, enthusiasm is difficult to awaken.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive to this day, and as proof of how overlapping the notions of the omnipotent and omniscient secret services are, it is sufficient.
