Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most stinking fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living – not only in Europe, but all over the world.
Could the country’s secret of success have something to do with the local appetite for rather nasty fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, damp sportswear.
And leave it there for a week.
So about you have to imagine the nasty smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow here, spectacular landscapes - and this stubborn smell in the air that just doesn't want to disappear.
Rakfisk is salt-stained trout, which - depending on how fragrant you would like your fish - is fermented in water for up to a year.
When in Norway the darkness comes over the country and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a feast here in Fagernes, which is dedicated to this, now, really very refreshing specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works at the local fire department, but also hosts the festival as a so-called "rakfish general".
People around us are consuming small fish cubes and consuming large amounts of alcohol.
“Many people like the aquavit more than the raccoon fish,” says Havard.
Spirits can suppress the smell.
I'll cost you a few bucks.
If you avoid bringing the rakfish near your nose, it’s not bad – like sushi, which has a pretty long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a completely different, much poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling options yet and fish were soaked in airtight saltwater vessels in the fall.
In the deepest winter, it was then removed after long fermentation and - undoubtedly with the help of alcohol dampened senses - consumed.
Even a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and migrated mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labour market, high wages and a comprehensive healthcare system.
Even from Sweden, the old rival, who was far richer than Norway not too long ago, immigrants flow.
Rakfisk is regarded as something important - as an essential, albeit strictly smelling part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the most expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs proudly 10 euros.
Norway does not often make it into the world press, and most people do not seem to be bothering.
Here one still hates to name Anders Breivik - that racist right-wing extremist who killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, we only refer to the "July 22 incident".
Norwegians find it hard to accept that someone in their peaceful country is capable of such brutal murders.
The main responsibility for Norway’s current wealth has been the growth of one of the world’s largest oil and gas industries since the early 1970s.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round tablets with mature rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and stinging blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a careful people.
Your English is just like that of most people here.
We're not very adorable, we don't like prahleria.
Norway has been very cautious about its oil wealth – a large part of the industry’s revenues are invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the global economic crisis, everyone was throwing around with money they didn’t even have, Norway kept its wallets closed.
“As long as we can ski in the winter and go hiking in the summer, we are happy,” says Anna.
"And of course eat raccoon fish," she adds with carefree laughter.
I stand in the snow and stand up for another dish - from Rakfisk I have enough.
An Elch burger like that is definitely something else. The juicy meat I like.
But in the evening, the stinky fish is on the menu again.
The hotel where I stay is one of several venues that organize a Rakfisk dinner where guests can vote for the best - or perhaps the most challenging smell - fish.
There is a live TV switch to a fly-covered showmaster surrounded by plates with Rakfisk.
The show is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
You clap and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by the aquavit.
But perhaps it is the severe thirst of the whole fish.
Mexico’s Enrique Pena Nieto faces a difficult start
As Mexico's future President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office, Will Grant from the BBC analyzes the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
At present, the traffic in Mexico City is very poor.
Even on better days, this is a city that is always clogged up, but on Monday a steel ring was built that shuts down several important traffic routes to the capital and causes chaos on the streets.
The goal, however, was not to disturb commuters on their way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will retain the presidency and take over the leadership of the nation.
He is facing a complex task.
Under the separatist government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has been able to prove itself economically well, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My government is strongly committed to reducing violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy with which we can achieve this goal.
Before joining the U.S. president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, vast part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are shared.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, one likes to remember it.
Residents of the resort attribute to it the development of tourism and the construction of the infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto built and which represents a major improvement over the fragile, hollow roads that once existed here.
Plaques with its name also hang outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and lasting changes from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the Pena Nietos party, which is the PRI.
In particular, with regard to security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so urgently needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party places high expectations on Enrique Pena Nieto.
The accusations of the opposition, the new president lacks substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has great plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the paved streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden among highway crossings and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are crucial urban in nature.
Earlier this year, the military was turned on to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
The bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left alone in the last two years on a spot in Brachland near a large landfill.
During the tenure of Governor Pena Nieto, more than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that even surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for their violence and the murder of innocent women.
Critics Pena Nietos are of the opinion that he has at least not adequately addressed the issue of the murder of women during his tenure.
But in the worst case, his government closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the downhill neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears as she shows me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes that she was murdered by her life partner.
