There were signs that she had been beaten, and the body starve had already been used.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall, next to a cross that bears a single word: justice.
But this one, the family said, has been denied so far.
The authorities have treated me as if I were a spokeswoman, a restless founder, a norwegian.
They want you to just accept their judgment and keep your mouth shut.
“But that’s not possible if there were so many form errors and failures,” she says.
If President Pena Nieto receives the presidency on Saturday, he will take on a big responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have suffered from violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has vowed to take special care of this problem during his tenure.
“I hope as president he is as he was as governor,” says PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But that is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
Prosecutor’s Office Claims Bradley Manning Has Not Complained About Abuse
Prosecutors oppose Bradley Manning’s accusations that he was abused in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks a rejection of the charge due to harsh conditions of detention
The liberated U.S. Army is accused of having stolen thousands of confidential documents
The U.S. Attorney’s Office on Friday sought to establish that military-free Bradley Manning — accused of revealing the largest confidential information in U.S. history — had failed on several occasions to complain about the alleged abuse he suffered in military custody.
At a cross-examination Mannings during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month prison term in Quantico, Virginia did not show any complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to reject the charge - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the harsh detention period - Manning had said he would have considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his tenure in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officials had filled out after their meeting with Manning during his detention in the Quantico military prison, where he had been detained from July 2010 to April 2011 under enhanced conditions of detention.
The officials asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein interviewed him on Friday for the forms, Manning admitted that he had rated the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the institution as a whole as "very professional".
The forms, so fine, did not contain complaints about abuse, although officials had directly questioned Manning about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they should deal with them, but they had not been recorded.
"They wrote (after discussing the concerns) "No problems" and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he was not complaining about his treatment when he met a committee in January 2011 that was supposed to investigate the suicidal thoughts he mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during this meeting had been to downgrade his observational status for "prevention of injury".
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status - which is a level under the threat of suicide - to his and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well, and get rid of the surveillance status to prevent injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning said on Thursday he was arrested and transferred to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Marine Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he was considering suicide in Kuwait and was once unconscious due to the heat.
Not knowing what had happened to him or in the outside world would have been burdensome.
“My world shrunk to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
When he was moved to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell – at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours – and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay in motion because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or even just go to bed.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated from the outside into his cell.
When he turned around at night and the guards could no longer see his face, they woke him up so that he would turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison of Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an allegation he had raised in his statement on Thursday - so he slept naked in his cell in Quantico one night and had to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had stated that during this count, he never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket.
During Friday's interrogation, Manning stated that he had closed a guard's order that he should have dropped the ceiling he could have covered himself with, but he admitted that no one had asked him to.
On Thursday, Manning had stated that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night and had previously tried to show an official that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used the tie of his underpants or his flip flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his detention experiences and drastically reduce his detention rate should he be convicted at his trial before the military court, which is set for the beginning of next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to minor offenses, while other charges that are considered too extreme are to be challenged.
Continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend and the prosecutor's office is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning was detained in accordance with the provisions that apply to all detainees held under the highest security measures in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include the harassment of the enemy, unlawful disclosure of intelligence on the Internet, the transfer of national defence information and the theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty in all the charges, he faces a life sentence.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis.
