On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport control when confusion spread within me.
Signs refer to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigns").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure of where to go.
I grew up in Central California and have been called “Mexican” all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Iren" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italian".
Later, I decided to go for “Mexican-American.”
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s home there was no need for abbreviations or punctuation.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in that language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I won’t let go of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in the queue for extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all those issues that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy. She is a reason why Mexicans today are just as likely to stay in Mexico instead of emigrating to the United States.
He wants to ally with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc following the example of the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue the war in Mexico against the drug cartel, even though he did not mention any details in this regard.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and resentful.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought on the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country’s leadership to give them more than half of their territory.
But for Mexicans who think for centuries and not minutes, memories of this event are not to be missed.
So as soon as a U.S. government official has even the slightest criticism of Mexico, complaints are heard in the Mexican press and among the country’s elites about how Americans are oppressing the sovereignty of their neighbours.
And the children of Montezuma go on the path of war.
And yet, Mexico’s biggest challenge lies in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There is more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason why so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is because at one point in our family tree a person - perhaps a parent or grandparent - did not get a chance in Mexico and headed north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty to them.
Not in Mexico.
And although we may now live the American dream, attend good schools and get good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream that we live - not the Mexican one.
Our identity is sometimes possibly blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This is clearly the case in the United States.
In addition, we are aware that we do not like many members of the Mexican leadership.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In your opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn’t failed in Mexico, they wouldn’t have gone.
And then we wouldn't be trapped behind the silk curtain now - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans take this to them.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know have the feeling that they belong neither to one nor to the other country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is rooted in none of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should have learned during my journey, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational community want to resume their connections to the diaspora.
They want to employ Mexican Americans as provisional “ambassadors” for Mexico, who represent their interests in the United States.
Let us tell our American colleagues about how great a visit to this country is and how pressure is exerted on the political leadership to intensify their ties to Mexico.
Oh, now.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And in the face of unfair income distribution, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through this alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet willing to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans are making a mess of how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected cornerstone of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to suffocate such hope in the germ.
In the midst of the usual confessions, countless buildings were laid in mud and ashes, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed – and for the first time rockets from Gaza were hit near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But even though Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not – Palestinians and Israelis have become part of these whims.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly pat situation could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism in view of the current situation seems anything but appropriate.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November continues, the fighting this week has strengthened the hard-pressed on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, are said to have pushed back the Israelis, even though its group itself suffered major losses.
Although several Hamas leaders have been killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are swept into one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And Hamas leaders could come to the conclusion that they have the time on their side.
As Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a reinvigorating regional power that was once considered Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken over Hamas’s party – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Exciting Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist imprint could stand before the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where the king of Hamas is overthrown.
And especially the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Mursi in Egypt – the by far the most populous and most important Arab country – on Israel’s southern flank has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the laizist despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the fraternity with Hamas is weakened and its leaders are more reliant on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could turn out to be an actor that cannot be pushed out by Israel and the United States itself.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw the opposite conclusion.
From a military standpoint, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, Iron Dome, has been able to prove itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
Israel will be able to sleep more peacefully for a while.
From a diplomatic point of view, the United States remains intact in its position, and many European countries have made Hamas responsible for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free from suicide bombers - not least thanks to the blockades that have been pushed into the West Bank and thus into the majority of any Palestinian state, but they continue to protect the Palestinians.
Netanyahu's Likud party has allied itself with an even more militant group ahead of the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these vicious Palestinians have to hide and leave a state of their own?
If they actually had control of the West Bank, wouldn’t they fire missiles just like their fellow fighters in the Gaza Strip?
No, it is better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Maybe the hardliners will be able to get through, but the Arab Spring could give them a streak through the bill.
Even if the Islamists now in power in Egypt and other countries have little left for Israel, they will first focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense policy is larger than that of its four Arab neighbours combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments in restoring their economy.
The fact that President Mursi is teaming up with Barack Obama to reach a ceasefire could be a promising sign – and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think more long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking slow steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination – a powder constitution that will undoubtedly one day explode in Israeli-occupied areas, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only exacerbate.
Bloody missions to repress Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand their diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside.
The correct answer is the one represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states in which Israel resigns for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give more influence to outsiders to enforce this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, must stop arms deliveries to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, complemented by an exchange of territories and a common Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also move Hamas and Fatah to an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the forthcoming application for UN observer status.
Obama must also contribute to Israel’s move to negotiations.
During his first term in office, he missed out on the idea of his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems as if he is equally inclined to participate.
But this is a sad, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a substantial interest in a stable Middle East.
This includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
