The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health when they carry 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he must climb down to the ground of his crater every day, where the sulfur-containing gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones that can weigh a total of up to 70 kilograms, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the skeletal paths made of stone.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes to climb at the turtle pace, while they have to keep the balance and carefully set their steps and not to erupt.
You know that every step can cost your life, as happened to a French tourist who crashed on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 eurocents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
Arrived up, they pave the way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tirelessly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scales that a mining society has set a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters.
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which since 1960 exploits the occurrences in the volcano and (never better) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocents) for every kilo of sulfur.
This is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 eurocent) to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the manufacture of plywood, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for the bleaching of sugar.
